                             Fig. 2B
                         ), even if the equivalence of 
                             R
                         * is imposed. The slower-growing phytoplankton types need a higher time-averaged nutrient concentration to compete with the faster growers and are excluded over time (
                                 10
                         ). Environmental variability creates a competitive structure such that the number of extant phytoplankton types can be reduced through competitive exclusion. Indeed, in the higher latitude, strongly seasonal marine environments where the global model solution exhibits lower diversity (
                             Fig. 1
                         ), high growth rate, and not low 
                             R
                         *, is the most appropriate measure of organismal fitness (
                                 12
                         ).
                     

